Figure 5 shows the Tafel polarization curves of the symmetrical cells based on the pulse-ECD PtNC and Pt film electrodes, respectively. As we can see from Fig. 5, the curves showed logarithmic current density (log J) as voltage (V). The exchange current density (J0) and the limiting diffusion current density (Jlim) could be obtained from these curves, which could be used to point out the electrocatalytic activities of the CEs. Comparing with the Pt film CE, the pulse-ECD PtNCs performed a larger exchange current density (J0), which meant that the PtNCs presented higher electrocatalytic activity and lower charge-transfer resistance at the electrolyte–electrode interface. J0 value was inversely related with Rct as according to Eq. (2) [39]Fig. 5
